  <!-- Article Content -->
  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>If you have ADHD, or have spent significant time with someone who does, you know the frustrating paradox at the center of the condition: the person cannot focus on the homework, but can focus for four uninterrupted hours on something they find genuinely interesting. They can't sustain attention in a meeting, but they can dissect a video game at a level of strategic depth that would exhaust most analysts.</p>

      <p>The standard framing of ADHD as an "attention deficit" has always sat uncomfortably with this paradox. It's not that the attention system is absent. It's that it operates on different terms. The brain seems selective in a way that undermines the "can't pay attention" model and suggests something more specific is going wrong.</p>

      <p>A study published in March 2026 has offered what may be the most structurally coherent explanation yet. The researchers, analyzing EEG data from children with and without ADHD diagnoses, found that during cognitively demanding tasks, ADHD brains periodically and involuntarily slip into patterns of electrical activity that resemble sleep — brief microsleeps, or what the researchers called "local sleep-like states," interspersed within otherwise wakeful brain function.</p>

      <p>The children weren't falling asleep. They were performing tasks, apparently awake, with eyes open. But in localized brain regions — particularly those responsible for sustained attention and executive function — the neurons were cycling in and out of sleep-like synchrony at intervals that directly correlated with attention lapses and task errors.</p>

      <p>It is, as findings go, quite clarifying.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="what-sleep-like-activity-actually-means" class="reveal">
      <h2>What Sleep-Like Activity Actually Means</h2>

      <p>To appreciate why this is significant, it helps to understand what distinguishes waking from sleeping brain activity at the neural level.</p>

      <p>During wakefulness, neurons in the cortex fire in an asynchronous, high-frequency pattern — a state of "desynchronized" activity associated with active information processing. During sleep, and particularly during slow-wave sleep, this gives way to synchronized, low-frequency oscillations in which neurons fire together in sweeping waves. This synchrony supports memory consolidation and cellular maintenance, but it is not compatible with coherent attention.</p>

      <p>Under normal circumstances, these two states are clearly separated. You're awake, or you're asleep. The regulatory systems governing arousal — involving the brainstem, thalamus, and orexin-producing neurons in the hypothalamus — work to maintain the wakeful state during the day and suppress sleep-like activity in contexts where it would be disruptive.</p>

      <p>What the 2026 study found is that in ADHD brains, this separation fails in a specific, task-dependent way. When cognitive demand is high — when sustained attention is required — the regulation breaks down locally. Patches of cortex slip into slow-wave-like synchrony for fractions of seconds to several seconds at a time, before returning to normal waking patterns. The rest of the brain may remain fully awake. But the circuits most needed for the task are, momentarily, somewhere between here and sleep.</p>

      <p>The researchers could predict attention lapses from these EEG signatures before the behavioral evidence of inattention appeared. The brain was failing before the child showed it.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"The ADHD brain, during a boring task, is not choosing to drift. It is doing what sleep-deprived brains do involuntarily — slipping into recovery states that the rest of the brain hasn't authorized."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="why-interesting-things-are-different" class="reveal">
      <h2>Why Interesting Things Are Different</h2>

      <p>This finding offers a compelling mechanistic account of the hyperfocus phenomenon — the capacity for deep, sustained attention on intrinsically motivating activities that seems to contradict the "deficit" model.</p>

      <p>The arousal systems that maintain wakefulness are not purely passive. They are modulated by dopamine, norepinephrine, and — critically — by interest, novelty, and anticipated reward. When a task is genuinely engaging, the dopaminergic reward pathways that are chronically underactive in ADHD become transiently activated, producing a neurochemical state that supports sustained arousal. The sleep-like intrusions don't occur because the arousal regulation system has something to work with.</p>

      <p>This is not "trying harder." It is a fundamental difference in what the brain needs to maintain wakeful, focused activity. For most people, the modest cognitive demand of a homework assignment or a routine meeting is sufficient to keep the arousal systems engaged. For ADHD brains, the threshold is higher — the content needs to be genuinely interesting or the system starts to drift.</p>

      <p>This reframing has implications for how ADHD is explained to children, to parents, and to adults who have spent decades interpreting their own fluctuating attention as a moral failing rather than a neurological signature.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="stimulants-revisited" class="reveal">
      <h2>Stimulants, Revisited</h2>

      <p>The finding also adds mechanistic clarity to why stimulant medications — methylphenidate and amphetamines — work for ADHD with an effectiveness that has always been somewhat disproportionate to the "attention deficit" framing.</p>

      <p>Stimulants elevate dopamine and norepinephrine in the prefrontal cortex and other attention-critical regions. These neurotransmitters are central to arousal regulation. By chemically elevating the arousal state, stimulants may be doing precisely what the ADHD brain needs: providing the neurochemical substrate to suppress local sleep-like intrusions during low-stimulation tasks.</p>

      <p>An earlier 2025 study using fMRI found that ADHD medications work less by "sharpening focus" and more by activating the brain's arousal and reward systems — reducing the likelihood that attention circuits will drift into the kind of disengagement that the 2026 EEG study now has an anatomical substrate for.</p>

      <p>These two pieces fit together well. The medications are essentially chemically simulating the neurochemical state that interesting tasks produce naturally.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
      <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">ADHD and Sleep: Key Numbers</h4>
