    </div>

    <section id="sleep-itself-is-implicated" class="reveal">
      <h2>Sleep Itself Is Implicated</h2>

      <p>There is an additional layer to the story. ADHD and sleep disorders are comorbid at rates that exceed coincidence. Between 50 and 70% of people with ADHD report chronic sleep problems: difficulty falling asleep, delayed sleep phase, restless sleep, difficulty waking, and persistent daytime sleepiness. These have typically been attributed to the condition's restless hyperactivity, the effects of stimulant medication, or simple co-occurrence of different disorders.</p>

      <p>The local-sleep model suggests a more integrated explanation. If the ADHD brain has a fundamentally compromised arousal regulation system — one that allows sleep-like states to intrude during wakefulness — it is plausible that the same dysregulation impairs the sharp separation between sleep and waking that healthy sleep architecture requires. A system that blurs the boundary in one direction may blur it in both.</p>

      <p>This is speculative at the current stage of evidence. But it generates a testable prediction: improving sleep quality and duration in ADHD patients should improve the daytime attention profile by reducing the sleep pressure that drives local sleep intrusions. The existing evidence on sleep and ADHD is consistent with this, though it has not been studied through this specific mechanistic lens.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="the-diagnostic-weight-of-laziness" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Diagnostic Weight of "Laziness"</h2>

      <p>This research is going to mean something to a lot of people for reasons that go beyond neuroscience.</p>

      <p>ADHD remains one of the most contested and stigmatized diagnoses in psychiatry. Children with the condition are disproportionately described as lazy, unmotivated, or deliberately disruptive. Adults who receive late diagnoses — and late diagnosis is common, particularly in women, who are historically underdiagnosed — frequently describe years of self-blame for what they now understand to be a neurological pattern. The "could do better if they tried" report card comment has a long and unkind history.</p>

      <p>The local-sleep finding is not merely interesting neuroscience. It is the kind of mechanistic evidence that shifts moral frames. The ADHD brain, during a boring task, is not choosing to drift. It is doing what sleep-deprived brains do involuntarily — slipping into recovery states that the rest of the brain hasn't authorized. Asking it to simply "pay attention" is not unlike asking someone to control their own blink reflex.</p>

      <p>The effort is real. The barrier is neurological.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"Asking the ADHD brain to simply 'pay attention' is not unlike asking someone to control their own blink reflex. The effort is real. The barrier is neurological."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="what-this-changes" class="reveal">
      <h2>What This Changes (and What It Doesn't)</h2>

      <p>The local-sleep model is a hypothesis with strong initial evidence, not a settled theory. The study requires replication. Its applicability across the full spectrum of ADHD presentations — which are diverse — has not been tested. It may explain inattentive-type ADHD more completely than hyperactive-impulsive presentations.</p>

      <p>What it does not do is resolve the controversy around ADHD diagnosis rates, stimulant prescribing practices, or the appropriate balance between pharmacological and behavioral interventions. Those debates involve social, ethical, and empirical dimensions that a single neuroimaging paradigm cannot close.</p>

      <p>What it does do is give researchers a new and specific target for both understanding and intervention — a measurable neural phenomenon that correlates with the core functional problem, that responds to known pharmacology, and that ties the disorder into a broader arousal regulation framework with implications for sleep, motivation, and the conditions under which any brain performs its best work.</p>

      <p>The deficit isn't in attention. It's in the system that decides when sleep is and isn't appropriate. That's a more precise description, and medicine tends to do better when its descriptions are precise.</p>
    </section>

